post_text: Congratulations Andrew Pelkey!
shared_text:
North Country Baseball
May 9 at 9:29 AM ·

North Country Baseball is pleased to announce that Schroon Lake senior Andrew Pelkey recently committed to Indiana Wesleyan University.

Pelkey, a standout left-handed pitcher for Bolton/Schroon Lake, earned Mountain & Valley Athletic Conference Most Valuable Player honors following the 2017 and 2019 seasons. He also earned first-team all-MVAC honors in 2018. Following the 2017 season he earned 4th Team All-New York State.

Indiana Wesleyan is an NAIA institution in Marion, IN and competes in the Crossroads League.

post_text: Love and positivity. Thanks to all of those on the front line.
shared_text:
Brian Premo
March 29 at 7:26 PM ·

It’s moments like these that remind me why this is the greatest city on earth.

Friday night there was an organized “event” where people in NYC decided to express their thanks and appreciation for all of the healthcare workers who have been working endlessly throughout this crisis.

It was meant to be a 2 minute event for city dwellers to give a round of applause - quite literally - from their windows and balconies to our healthcare workers.

It has now turned into a 10 minute long, nightly event with cow bells, cheering, honking...you name it. It’s basically what it sounds like when the NYC marathon snakes through the city. And it’s been expanded to ALL essential workers - healthcare, grocery stores, first responders, MTA, etc.

This. More of this. Please thank anyone and everyone you know in healthcare. They are on the front lines and deserve every ounce of appreciation we have.

I like to think that it’s moments like these that led to the saying “I Love New York”... THANK YOU!!!

#clapbecausewecare
#ILoveNY
#thankahealthcareworker
#covid_19

post_text: After they were told the games were cancelled and given the choice of how to move forward all they wanted to do is play ball. So they picked teams and battled on the court one last time. I think back to all of the time they spent over the last four years and can’t help but feel crushed that their season has to end like this. This is an unbelievable group of young men that I am honored to call my guys and more importantly my friends.

post_text:
SL girls upend Wells last night.

SCHROON LAKE 70

WELLS 18

SCHROON LAKE — Malena Gereau piled up 27 points in the Wildcats' defeat of the Indians.

Gereau had three treys in the game, and Schroon Lake owned a commanding 40-10 lead at half.

Jocelyn Scribner finished with six points to help Wells.

—

Schroon Lake 70, Wells 18

Wells (18)

Braunius 0-3-3, Brooks 2-1-5, Simola 0-0-0, Robinson 0-0-0, O'Rourke 2-0-4, Scribner 3-0-6, Purchase 0-0-0. Totals: 7-4-18.

Schroon Lake (70)

Cutting 4-0-8, Kowal 0-2-2, Buell 1-0-2, Maisonville 2-0-4, Hayden 4-0-9, Baker 4-0-8, Shaughnessy 4-0-8, Storman 1-0-2, Gereau 8-8-27. Totals: 28-10-70.

Halftime- Schroon Lake, 40-10.

3 point goals- Schroon Lake (4) Hayden, Gereau 3.

Sports fans:

In preparation of tomorrows sectional game.

Please note that the school parking lot will close at 2:30 tomorrow to line up the busses and allow our students to safely board our busses. The lot will remain closed until the busses have come back from the after School run.

If parking on school grounds please make sure to only park in designated parking spots. Parking outside of designated parking spots creates hazards in case of an emergency.

Please note that cars may park in the church parking lot directly across from the school, the vacant lot just north of the school on route 9 and the Topps parking lot just south of the school.

Thank you for your understanding.

SCHROON LAKE 3

NEWCOMB 0

SCHROON LAKE — It took the second-seeded Wildcats a while to get on the scoreboard, but when they did, they struck often for all three of their goals.

post_text:
Great Hard-Fought Game Girls. Congratulations on a great season.

KEENE 2

SCHROON LAKE 1, OT

KEENE VALLEY — Haylie Buysse's second goal of the game, at 6:28 of the first overtime, lifted third-seeded Keene over the sixth-seeded and upset-minded Wildcats.

Keene held a 21-8 shot advantage, but had its hands full while advancing on.

The game was scoreless before Buysse opened the scoring midway through the second half. But, Victoria Buell's goal less than four minutes later pulled Schroon Lake even.

It remained tied until Alyssa Summo assisted on Buysse's game-winner.

Sophia Johnson stopped six shots for Keene. Emma Haneman finished with 19 saves for Schroon Lake.

CROWN POINT 1

CROWN POINT — Andrew Pelkey and Cian Bresnahan each registered two goals for the Wildcats' victory over the Panthers.

Schroon Lake's Ethan Fariss opened scoring, and Tommy Dorsett put Crown Point on the board with a goal at the 23:58 mark of the first half.

“Schroon Lake played a nice possession game and has made big leaps as a team from last year and the first time we played them,” Panthers coach Randy Pertak said. “This was Senior Night for Dylan Sours, Cameron Harrington and Joe Safford. They have contributed to the success of our program over the last couple of years. Tommy Dorsett scored his first varsity goal (Friday).”
